\fs28 3.2 Risk findings:\par
\par
1.Review the Risk Assessment Methodology:\par
\fs22  Familiarize yourself with the chosen risk assessment methodology that will guide your findings. Ensure you understand the key components, such as risk identification, probability assessment, impact assessment, risk categorization, and mitigation strategies.\par
\fs28 2.Gather Information:\par
\fs22  Collect relevant data and information about the organization, project, or context being assessed. This may include historical data, incident reports, industry regulations, stakeholder interviews, and internal documentation. The information gathered should help you identify potential risks and understand their impact.\par
\fs28 3.Identify Risks: \par
\fs22 Use the information gathered to identify specific risks that could impact the organization or project. Consider both internal and external risks, including operational, financial, legal, reputational, and strategic risks. Involve relevant stakeholders to ensure a comprehensive identification process.\par
\fs28 4.Assess Probability:\par
\fs22  Evaluate the likelihood or probability of each identified risk occurring. This can be done using qualitative or quantitative methods, depending on the available data and expertise. Use historical data, statistical analysis, expert opinions, or probability models to determine the likelihood of each risk event.\par
\fs28 5.Assess Impact:\par
\fs22  Determine the potential impact or consequences of each identified risk. Consider various factors, such as financial, operational, reputational, legal, or safety impacts. Assess the severity and magnitude of each risk's potential consequences. This assessment can also be qualitative or quantitative, depending on the data and analysis methods used.\par
\fs28 6.Determine Risk Level:\par
\fs22  Combine the probability and impact assessments to determine the overall risk level for each identified risk. This can be done by using a risk assessment matrix or other categorization methods. Categorize risks into high, medium, or low risk levels to prioritize them effectively.\par
\fs28 7.Develop Mitigation Strategies:\par
\fs22  Based on the risk assessment findings, develop strategies to mitigate or manage the identified risks. Identify appropriate risk controls, preventive measures, and contingency plans to reduce the probability or impact of risks. Assign responsibilities, define action plans, and establish monitoring mechanisms to ensure the effectiveness of the mitigation strategies.\par
\fs28 8.Document and Communicate Findings: \par
\fs22 Document the risk assessment findings in a clear and concise manner. Include the identified risks, their probability, impact, and risk levels, as well as the recommended mitigation strategies. Communicate the findings to relevant stakeholders, such as management, project teams, or regulatory bodies, to ensure everyone is aware of the risks and the proposed mitigation measures.\par
\fs28 9.Monitor and Review:\fs22\par
 Continuously monitor the effectiveness of the implemented risk mitigation strategies. Regularly review and update the risk assessment findings to account for any changes in the organization, project, or external environment. Conduct periodic reassessments to identify new risks or changes in the existing risk landscape\par
